<node id="&quot;PHILIPPE AGHION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A French economist discussing pension reform, advocating for a points-based system and a retirement age of 63 with a review in 2027. He emphasizes the economic need for higher employment rates and productivity."&lt;SEP&gt;"A French economist who identifies as a social democrat, arguing against the label of neoliberal and discussing economic systems, social welfare, and international comparisons."&lt;SEP&gt;"A participant in the discussion about economic reforms and shared sacrifices in France."&lt;SEP&gt;"A speaker who describes two economic currents in France: a social democracy of production and a zero-sum game mentality, advocating for innovation to enable redistribution."&lt;SEP&gt;"An economist and public figure discussing French fiscal policy, advocating for shared sacrifices and a comprehensive review of tax credits and patrimonial holdings."&lt;SEP&gt;"An economist and speaker who expresses respect for RNF voters, discusses the feeling of being despised, and emphasizes the need for inclusion."&lt;SEP&gt;"An economist who argues against the Zucman tax, explaining its negative impact on AI development in France and discusses AI's effects on growth and employment."&lt;SEP&gt;"Philippe Aghion is a participant in the discussion who briefly interjects to agree with the points-based system approach to pension reform."&lt;SEP&gt;"Philippe Aghion is an economist and commentator who advocates for pension reform, increased employment rates, and productivity growth as means to sustain France's social system."&lt;SEP&gt;"Philippe Aghion is an economist and participant in the discussion, contributing ideas about France's role in Europe, the need for republican values, and a modernized Gaullist vision."&lt;SEP&gt;"Philippe Aghion is an economist participating in the discussion. He highlights the technological decline of Europe and France compared to the US and China, and argues that innovation and productivity are essential to finance and sustain the European social model."&lt;SEP&gt;"Philippe Aghion is an economist who provides analysis on the French resistance to pension reform. He cites a 'culture of management' in some French companies and a lack of employee consultation as reasons for unhappiness at work, contrasting it with practices in Germany and Scandinavia."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-14e4b66af7e240a6e454da971c593ede&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4d1c98cbcc5c65952fc4e69108ecc5d8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-118614beec01eb5355b255debcebf23c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5a6c18fd60d725c0dd2b48e489b44a89&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b901d171dd5785e4ce0ac05b882d406d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5fb2a574f750d88794cd45cf0819ffea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2f7aa0930a810d99a7277de4db2ec96f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f44f51fafa9fb2ab36dcce22ab1fd71d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-61659a768934b7ee8b99c4caa2dc73f3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c40155ff1959faacc40ac81a1bd82732&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bc173c20fe16236b49dc39f9e7d15fcf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c0fa7905a87ac3fcff901f5c962535c9</data>
</node>
